<subSubSection id="E4AE0607929925C35B9C09E6EC2FDD3E" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="C5CFA68FEDC1C043466C76A135DFC36F" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1FF0E8AEB6A057C14B5C5405B33C277C" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
<bibRefCitation id="608E21C2BBD767005A2EAA9D4B04CFD0" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3742.1.1" author="Pinho, LC" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="1 - 78" refId="B11" refString="Pinho, LC, Mendes, HF, Andersen, T, 2013. Revision of Beardius Reiss et Sublette, 1985 (Diptera: Chironomidae), with the description of twenty new species. Zootaxa 3742: 1 - 78, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3742.1.1" title="Revision of Beardius Reiss et Sublette, 1985 (Diptera: Chironomidae), with the description of twenty new species." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3742.1.1" volume="3742" year="2013">Pinho et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
found that the &quot;presence of apical thin setae on inferior volsella&quot; (character 74, state 1), i.e. a group of two, rarely three, slender simple setae at the very tip of the inferior volsella, in addition to subapical, stouter setae, is the only synapomorphy of 
<taxonomicName id="9C33A47A759BEC090F7CF1FE87EFA613" authorityName="Reiss &amp; Sublette" authorityYear="1985" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Beardius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Beardius" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3E95690DA91E190936EF8BF5F33490D9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Beardius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Reiss &amp; Sublette, 1985 in the adult stage. In fact, the character is shared by all species of 
<taxonomicName id="CA00F7380D2F58983CCE36FC673490CD" authorityName="Reiss &amp; Sublette" authorityYear="1985" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Beardius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Beardius" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="97FD4668F0D33AEB42FA7CA95713767C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Beardius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is not found elsewhere, except in 
<taxonomicName id="A431040C1DA8F2219B3CBE93B8E04A64" authorityName="Pinho &amp; Andersen" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Pinho &amp; Andersen" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Nilothauma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilothauma longissimum" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longissimum">
<emphasis id="3F8CEB576ADEAED547CE4E9CACA4CBA1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Nilothauma longissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mendes &amp; Andersen, 2009, a species that was considered to be sister to all remaining 
<taxonomicName id="05E7790D516E7AC02CD5E46B317CE6E1" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Nilothauma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilothauma" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3D90B0B77ADF796F26013D09273F3BDF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Nilothauma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="398367E18A44B248AB091381FC007D28" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" author="Mendes, HF" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Mendes, HF, Andersen, T, 2009. Neotropical Nilothauma Kieffer, 1921, with the description of thirteen new species (Diptera: Chironomidae). Zootaxa 2063: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" title="Neotropical Nilothauma Kieffer, 1921, with the description of thirteen new species (Diptera: Chironomidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" volume="2063" year="2009">Mendes and Andersen (2009)</bibRefCitation>
in a phylogenetic analysis with 
<taxonomicName id="2D10A9FE04889EF444E5D34852D3288E" class="Hexapoda" family="Chironomidae" genus="Paratendipes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paratendipes" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6E033952E3FC292A0EA1BED9B0DED180" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Paratendipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kieffer and 
<taxonomicName id="7102EFA255DD85C774BAA68C48FDF1C0" authorityName="Malloch" authorityYear="1915" class="Hexapoda" family="Chironomidae" genus="Pseudochironomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudochironomus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5E0216F620F2C4D14D2B58E484C957BE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Pseudochironomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Malloch as outgroups. The comparatively-high antennal ratio in 
<taxonomicName id="A6B282A4910D0FA72B5BF0EF4F0A4C67" genus="N." lsidName="N. longissimum" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="longissimum">
<emphasis id="CFA6236A4AD5B05D9AFACA7016E414D4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">N. longissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(AR&gt; 1.00) is the only exception in 
<taxonomicName id="D1F2B706AF3F7B0B0572A14AF164B09D" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Nilothauma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilothauma" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9B7D4FB4FD65E2072D11D215770B832E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Nilothauma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which generally have very low antennal ratios (AR &lt;0.40). Further, the venarum ratio (VR) seems to be low in 
<taxonomicName id="A66D7B42DB16BF051C2065D132A86460" genus="N." lsidName="N. longissimum" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="longissimum">
<emphasis id="65720A1DFEE93D84992BFB51B08A3016" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">N. longissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
compared to other 
<taxonomicName id="EA0B3C6D2CEE056D8B38FC0ADDE67EBB" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Nilothauma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilothauma" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9EB540324AE5FDF5A590E9412B33BB11" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Nilothauma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species; other characters in 
<taxonomicName id="4432BFCE3F7806A9E710BA806D13A867" genus="N." lsidName="N. longissimum" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="longissimum">
<emphasis id="BD9C6A1194ADE6D2233F7870E70E6565" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">N. longissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are consistent with the current diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="2C30C9C8BEC987DFBBA9E91EAE6E8A95" authorityName="Reiss &amp; Sublette" authorityYear="1985" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Beardius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Beardius" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="149DA9E0B236A46E1C4BB244221B005D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Beardius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We therefore propose the new combination and emend the diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="79ABB15E3859A39B2C71951442595C96" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Nilothauma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilothauma" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CB470FE9A944C1264E7AD486173AE731" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Nilothauma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
accordingly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9FB4767720254BBA2C63760C11F711B" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="4156256CDFF52723086D024C1628EBDC" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5C47D8395711728F04236364ED617F47" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
The species was originally described from 
<normalizedToken id="C9EF4A0CA478383CEEE3E612D607E34E" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Paulo State, south-eastern Brazil by 
<bibRefCitation id="16D3362D930CE3722F061B6C41DD7C84" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" author="Mendes, HF" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Mendes, HF, Andersen, T, 2009. Neotropical Nilothauma Kieffer, 1921, with the description of thirteen new species (Diptera: Chironomidae). Zootaxa 2063: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" title="Neotropical Nilothauma Kieffer, 1921, with the description of thirteen new species (Diptera: Chironomidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2063.1.1" volume="2063" year="2009">Mendes and Andersen (2009)</bibRefCitation>
; the range is now extended to Bahia State in north-eastern Brazil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
